% ============================================================
%  Chapter 5: System Implementation -- Results and Discussion
% ============================================================

\subsection{Introduction}

The preceding chapters established the project context, surveyed the literature, formalised requirements, and selected a system architecture through systematic AHP analysis. This chapter documents what was actually built. It covers the hardware commissioning of the iMRP500 platform, the fabrication of the custom body shell, the development of the software stack, and the integration and validation tests that were conducted to verify that the system meets its stated requirements.

Two significant decisions were made during the second semester that are worth explaining before the technical content. First, the team departed from TurtleBot and iCreate~3 --- the platforms studied extensively in semester one --- in favour of the iMRP500, a Chinese-manufactured industrial mobile chassis. Second, the project scope broadened from a strictly medical deployment to a general-purpose autonomous service robot framework that uses healthcare as its primary validation environment. Both decisions are grounded in engineering reasoning and are documented in the sections that follow.

% -------------------------------------------------------
\subsection{Platform Transition: From TurtleBot to iMRP500}
% -------------------------------------------------------

The first semester was spent studying the TurtleBot~4 and iCreate~3 platforms in simulation and reviewing their documentation in depth. That work was not wasted --- it built a solid foundation in ROS~2, SLAM, Nav2, sensor fusion, and mobile robot design that carried directly into the implementation phase.

When it came time to procure hardware, however, the team faced conditions that made both original platforms untenable.

\paragraph{iRobot and the iCreate~3.}
iRobot, the manufacturer of the iCreate~3 base, entered bankruptcy proceedings at the point the team needed to commit to a purchase. A Chinese acquisition attempt was underway, and the long-term availability of spare parts, firmware updates, and technical support was genuinely uncertain. Building an entire final-year project on a platform in that state, with a fixed 1,500~OMR budget and an eight-week countdown to the Engineering Gathering, was assessed as an unacceptable risk.

\paragraph{Structural limitations.}
Neither the TurtleBot~4 nor the iCreate~3 offer any engineered mounting interface for a body structure. Both platforms are designed as flat, low-profile bases. Attaching a tall ergonomic shell --- as the project required for display positioning, storage, and patient-facing aesthetics --- would have required improvised fixturing, creating mechanical instability that would have undermined the entire physical design.

\paragraph{The Chinese mobile-chassis market.}
The team conducted a systematic evaluation of eight Chinese-manufactured robot chassis platforms, reviewing vendor documentation, ROS~2 support status, sensor suites, payload ratings, and structural mounting options for each. The candidates included the Reeman Moon Knight, Wheeltec S100, Timo AI Robot, Bao Xiaomi Mini, Uwant T5, and the iMRP500 by NeoChassis. The comparison revealed that Chinese industrial platforms had, in several respects, advanced ahead of the Western academic platforms originally considered: higher payload ratings, integrated industrial-grade sensors, longer battery runtime, and support for the full ROS~2 navigation stack.

\paragraph{Selection: iMRP500.}
The iMRP500 scored highest under the same AHP criteria applied in Chapter~4 (Reliability~47\%, Development Speed~30\%, Cost~15\%, Customisability~8\%), achieving a score of~6.76. Competing options were constrained by payload ($<$10~kg for most), limited sensor integration, or absence of published ROS~2 support. The iMRP500 is a circular differential-drive chassis, 500~mm in diameter, with 50~kg payload capacity, a built-in 360° TOF LiDAR, an RGBD structured-light depth camera, a 6-axis IMU, a 24~V/20~Ah Li-ion battery rated for 12~hours at no load, and an onboard X86 industrial PC running Ubuntu~20.04 with ROS~1 (bridgeable to ROS~2). Its circular footprint constrains the upper body to the same diameter, which is a hard requirement for LiDAR clearance: any part of the robot that overhangs the base perimeter will create blind spots in the costmap. The iMRP500 is sold new at approximately USD~2,000 and was procured second-hand at USD~1,400.

