% -------------------------------------------------------
\subsection{Scope Refinement: General-Purpose Service Robot}
% -------------------------------------------------------

A parallel discovery during the second semester shaped the project direction in an equally significant way. Medical environments are among the slowest sectors to adopt new technology. Certification timelines, regulatory approval, hospital procurement cycles, and liability frameworks make deploying a novel robot in a clinical setting extremely difficult and time-consuming --- far beyond the scope of a final-year project. Building a system framed exclusively as a medical device would effectively make it impossible to demonstrate real-world utility within the project timeline.

The team therefore reframed the project scope: TAMRA (Task-Agnostic Modular Robotic Apparatus) is an autonomous service robot framework, with healthcare as its primary validation environment but with explicit design choices that allow it to generalise to any service context --- facilities management, hospitality, airports, and campus environments. The core technical contributions --- semantic task orchestration, hybrid hardware synthesis, and ROS~2-based navigation --- are domain-independent. The validation scenario chosen for this project is a hospital corridor, but the architecture is not medically locked.

This is not a narrowing of ambition. The commercial hospital robot market is dominated by single-function platforms costing USD~12,000 to USD~47,500. TAMRA demonstrates that the same functional envelope --- autonomous navigation, voice-driven AI interaction, item delivery, and remote telepresence --- can be achieved at USD~3,200 on an open, extensible architecture. That cost compression, and the open-source nature of the stack, is the engineering contribution.

% -------------------------------------------------------
\subsection{Hardware Implementation}
% -------------------------------------------------------

\subsubsection{iMRP500 Commissioning and Reverse Engineering}

The iMRP500 is delivered as a fully integrated chassis with a proprietary ROS~1 navigation stack running on the onboard X86 PC. The vendor provides a graphical operator application and a Chinese-language communication protocol document. Commissioning the platform for research use required reverse-engineering the communication layer.

\paragraph{Network architecture.}
The chassis exposes two network interfaces. Over Ethernet (robot IP~\texttt{192.168.20.22}), the onboard PC runs \texttt{rosbridge\_server} on port~9090, which accepts WebSocket connections and exchanges JSON-encoded ROS messages. A second interface, \texttt{web\_video\_server} on port~9099, streams MJPEG video over HTTP. The team connected an external computer to this Ethernet interface and mapped the full topic and service graph.

\paragraph{Sensor topology.}
The chassis runs 16 ROS nodes concurrently. The sensors accessible over the bridge are:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{2D LiDAR} (\texttt{/scan}, \texttt{sensor\_msgs/LaserScan}): 360° TOF scan, 20~m range, used as the primary localisation and obstacle-avoidance input.
    \item \textbf{RGBD depth camera} (\texttt{/upcamera/rgb/image\_raw}, \texttt{/upcamera/depth/image\_raw}): structured-light sensor mounted pointing upward, detecting obstacles above the LiDAR scan plane (e.g., tables, counter overhangs).
    \item \textbf{IMU} (6-axis attitude): fused with wheel odometry for pose prediction.
    \item \textbf{Wheel encoders} (\texttt{/mobile\_base/sensors/core}): differential-drive odometry.
    \item \textbf{Ultrasonic sensors}: three-point frontal coverage for close-range ($<$0.5~m) detection.
\end{itemize}

\paragraph{Navigation stack.}
The costmap planner operates with four stacked layers: an obstacle layer fed by the 2D LiDAR scan (4~m range, 0.6~m maximum height), an upward-camera layer for overhead obstacle detection (3.5~m range, 2~m maximum height), an equivalent downward-camera layer, and an inflation layer with a 0.8~m radius at scaling factor~10. The local costmap updates at 8~Hz over a 3$\times$3~m window at 0.03~m resolution; the global costmap updates at 4~Hz over 10$\times$10~m at 0.05~m resolution. The positioning accuracy specified by the manufacturer is $\pm$5~cm.

\paragraph{Internal architecture.}
Physical inspection of the electronics revealed a three-layer construction that explains the platform's cost efficiency. The bottom layer uses commodity CNC stepper-motor driver boards (equivalent to industrial DM542T units), identifiable by their green terminal blocks and LED status indicators. The mid layer is a standard industrial mini-PC with multiple USB and Ethernet ports. The top layer uses 3D-printer-ecosystem control boards for sensor interfacing and motor sequencing. The drive motors are hub motors sourced from the electric scooter industry. This architecture substitutes commodity industrial and hobby-electronics components for custom ASICs, reducing manufacturing cost without sacrificing reliability at service-robot duty cycles.

\paragraph{Service interface.}
Navigation goals are dispatched via the \texttt{/poi} ROS service using named waypoints stored in the chassis map database. Additional services expose self-diagnosis (\texttt{/self\_diagnosis}), speed mode selection (\texttt{/velocity\_control}, modes~0--8 for safe/balance/efficiency at low/mid/high speed), virtual wall management (\texttt{/append\_virtual\_walls}), and map operations (\texttt{/node\_manager\_control} for SLAM start/stop and map save). Status codes covering navigation state (600--609), cross-floor transitions (630--647), patrol sequences (650--660), and fault conditions (99, 106, 108, 109) were catalogued from protocol analysis and live testing.

\subsubsection{Body Shell Design and Fabrication}

The body shell is the structural interface between the 500~mm circular chassis and the robot's human-facing components: the display, the storage compartment, and the external surface that users and patients interact with. Eleven functional requirements constrained the design:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item Display tilted at 40° from horizontal for ergonomic use at standing and seated heights.
    \item Display recess sized to allow a future larger screen without structural change (5~mm step, 360$\times$260~mm outer, 320$\times$210~mm active area).
    \item Internal trays for secure transport; external compartment for accessible delivery.
    \item Footprint not exceeding the 500~mm chassis diameter (LiDAR clearance).
    \item Added mass not exceeding 12~kg (chassis centre-of-mass stability limit at 600~mm).
    \item Total height not exceeding 1,100~mm (tipping stability).
    \item Hospital-grade materials: no sharp edges, surfaces compatible with standard disinfectant protocols.
    \item Concealed cable routing between the tablet, display driver, and chassis.
    \item Manufacturable within Oman using locally available trades and materials.
    \item Budget not exceeding 300~OMR ($\approx$USD~780).
    \item Warm, approachable aesthetic to reduce patient anxiety in clinical environments.
\end{enumerate}

\paragraph{Design process.}
The design was developed in three stages. In the first stage, generative AI image synthesis (Google Gemini) was used to rapidly explore hundreds of aesthetic directions. This is not a replacement for engineering design; it is a concept-space compression tool. Within hours, the team could assess proportions, surface finishes, and display positions that would have required days of CAD iteration. The converged concept is a tapered vertical silhouette with a central oak-veneer accent panel, a recessed display at the top, and an integrated rear storage compartment.

In the second stage, the selected concept image was fed into an AI-based 3D mesh generator (Hunyuan3D~v3.1), producing an initial 50,000-face mesh. This captured the organic curvature of the concept but introduced fabrication-incompatible geometry: overhangs beyond the 500~mm base radius, incorrect storage compartment proportions, and no engineering tolerances.

In the third stage, the mesh was used as a reference for parametric reconstruction in Autodesk Fusion~360. All dimensions were set as parameters, tolerances were specified, and fabrication-ready engineering drawings were produced. The finalised dimensions are: 900.27~mm total height, 500~mm base width (chassis interface), 400~mm waist width (narrowest), 210.23~mm storage compartment depth, 40° display tilt, and an upper tray designed to be removable for display servicing.

