    \caption{Rear view of parametric model showing the removable upper tray that provides access to the display mounting hardware and cable management without disassembling the full shell.}
    \label{fig:back_view}
\end{figure}

\paragraph{Material selection.}
Three-dimensional printing was rejected early as cost-prohibitive for large curved panels and structurally insufficient for service-robot duty. The team evaluated fibreglass layup, vacuum-formed ABS, sheet aluminium, and combinations of wood and acrylic. Foam sculpting was explored as an intermediate method: CNC-machined rigid foam can produce complex curved surfaces indistinguishable from moulded plastic, is non-conductive, lightweight, and can be veneered. This technique is used extensively in film and exhibition prop construction.

The final material selection uses a structural wood subframe (locally sourced, cut by a Muscat carpentry workshop) as the load-bearing skeleton, with acrylic sheet panels for dimensional precision on flat faces (particularly the display surround, where the 5~mm step tolerance is critical), and oak-veneer film applied over the wood surfaces for the final aesthetic finish. This combination satisfied all eleven requirements: it is manufacturable in Oman, within budget, lighter than metal alternatives, and produces a warm surface finish that clinical psychology literature associates with reduced patient anxiety in healthcare environments.

\paragraph{Fabrication status.}
Body shell fabrication was completed in April~2026. Physical integration with the chassis --- cable routing, display mounting, tray installation, and final panel alignment --- followed. Figure~\ref{fig:real_robot} shows the integrated system.

\begin{figure}[H]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.75\textwidth]{real_integration.jpg}
    \caption{TAMRA after full integration: iMRP500 chassis, fabricated body shell with oak-veneer panels, and 10-inch touch display mounted at 40°.}
    \label{fig:real_robot}
\end{figure}

\subsubsection{Display and Tablet Integration}

The human-interface component is a 10-inch industrial-grade Android tablet (Rockchip RK3566 SoC, 2~GB RAM, 1280$\times$800 IPS touch display, Android~11). An industrial-grade device was chosen over a consumer tablet for two reasons: it supports always-on kiosk operation without sleep-mode interruptions, and it is rated for extended continuous operation. The tablet runs the MACS face and orchestrator software in Fully Kiosk Browser, which locks the display to the robot-UI application and prevents users from navigating away.

\paragraph{Dual-network routing problem.}
The most technically demanding part of the tablet integration was the network configuration. The tablet must simultaneously maintain:
\begin{itemize}
    \item An Ethernet connection to the robot chassis (IP \texttt{192.168.20.100}, subnet \texttt{192.168.20.x}) for low-latency ROS WebSocket communication; and
    \item A WiFi connection to the campus network for internet access, cloud AI APIs (Gemini, ElevenLabs), and MQTT telemetry.
\end{itemize}

Android's default behaviour routes all traffic over a single interface, discarding the other. If WiFi is connected, Ethernet is ignored; if Ethernet is active, WiFi may be suppressed. The team evaluated several approaches: Speedify (dual-channel bonding app --- unstable on Android~11), a separate ESP32 MQTT bridge (adds latency and a hardware dependency), swapping Android for Linux (loses the kiosk application ecosystem), USB WiFi tethering from a phone (introduces another device to manage), and 4G/LTE dongle (recurring cost and requires SIM). The solution that worked reliably is a boot daemon script deployed via ADB (Android Debug Bridge) that runs as a background service and explicitly sets static routes: robot-subnet traffic (\texttt{192.168.20.x}) is forced over the \texttt{eth0} interface, while all other traffic uses the \texttt{wlan0} default gateway. The daemon is started at boot via an ADB shell command and survives the Fully Kiosk Browser session.

\paragraph{Voice interface evolution.}
Three voice pipeline approaches were prototyped before arriving at the final configuration:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{OpenAI Live Model}: Integrated and tested. Voice quality was adequate but the interaction felt stilted, with awkward latency distribution that made conversation feel unnatural. Limited tool-calling flexibility constrained what the robot could do mid-conversation.
    \item \textbf{ElevenLabs Conversational AI (standalone)}: Significantly more natural voice synthesis, but the round-trip latency was perceived as noticeably slow, particularly when combined with the ROS command dispatch overhead. Standalone mode did not give sufficient control over tool routing.
    \item \textbf{ElevenLabs + Gemini~3.1 Live (current)}: When Google released Gemini~3.1 Live, the pipeline was migrated. Gemini~3.1 Live provides real-time bidirectional audio processing with tool-calling capability baked in, and it eliminated the layered latency of the previous configurations. ElevenLabs is retained for voice synthesis quality. This configuration is the one used for all validation measurements.
\end{enumerate}

% -------------------------------------------------------
\subsection{Software Implementation}
% -------------------------------------------------------

The software system has two main components: the tablet application that runs on the robot, and the central command dashboard that runs in any browser and communicates remotely over MQTT.

\subsubsection{Three-Tier Architecture}

The software is structured in three communicating tiers:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Robot Layer}: The iMRP500 onboard X86 PC runs the ROS~1 navigation stack, sensor drivers, costmap pipeline, and SLAM/localisation nodes. It exposes the \texttt{rosbridge} WebSocket on port~9090 and video on port~9099.
    \item \textbf{Bridge Layer}: The tablet application (a single self-contained HTML file, approximately 4,800 lines) connects to the robot via Ethernet WebSocket and to the cloud via WiFi. It hosts the mission engine, task queue, cron scheduler, MQTT bridge, MACS animated face, and the voice orchestration pipeline. Using a single HTML file was a deliberate choice: it requires no installation, runs in any WebKit browser, and can be updated by replacing one file over ADB.
    \item \textbf{Cloud Layer}: Google Gemini~3 Flash (orchestration LLM, USD~3/M tokens, 1M-token context window), ElevenLabs Conversational AI (voice synthesis and ASR), and HiveMQ Cloud (MQTT broker, TLS-encrypted WSS) provide the AI and telemetry back-end.
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Semantic Task Orchestrator}

The orchestrator is the core engineering contribution of the software layer. Given a free-form voice command in English or Arabic --- for example, ``take this document to the nurses' station and then go back to the lobby'' --- the orchestrator invokes Gemini~3 Flash with a structured prompt that includes the robot's current battery level, position, known waypoints, and active task queue as live context variables. Gemini returns a mission plan as a sequence of typed steps:

\[
s_i \in \{\texttt{navigate}(w),\;\texttt{speak}(m),\;\texttt{display}(d),\;\texttt{photo},\;\texttt{wait}(t)\}
\]

where $w$ is a named waypoint, $m$ is a spoken message, $d$ is display content, and $t$ is a wait duration in seconds. The plan is returned as a server-sent event (SSE) stream, and the mission engine begins executing the first step before the full plan has been generated. This streaming execution reduces perceived latency: the robot starts moving while the LLM is still producing step two.

The mission engine maintains a priority queue with five states: \textsc{pending} $\to$ \textsc{running} $\to$ \{\textsc{completed}, \textsc{failed}, \textsc{cancelled}\}. A 1~Hz tick evaluates the queue and dispatches navigation goals to the chassis via the \texttt{/poi} ROS service. Supported mission types are:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{GO\_TO}: Single-waypoint navigation.
    \item \textbf{DELIVERY}: Multi-stop sequence (up to five waypoints), with confirmation at each stop before proceeding.
    \item \textbf{PATROL}: Looping route through a defined set of points of interest.
    \item \textbf{AUTO\_CHARGE}: Battery-triggered autonomous return to the docking station (configurable threshold, default 20\%).
\end{itemize}

A built-in cron scheduler accepts standard five-field POSIX cron expressions, enabling recurring autonomous missions such as an hourly patrol or a nightly return-to-dock without manual intervention.

\subsubsection{MQTT Bridge and Remote Dashboard}

Remote operation is provided through an MQTT bridge over HiveMQ Cloud (WSS, TLS-encrypted). The bridge publishes robot state at 1~Hz: pose, battery percentage, task queue contents, navigation status, and LiDAR scan data. Large payloads (occupancy grid maps, up to several hundred kilobytes) are chunked into 64~KB segments and reassembled on the subscriber side.

The central command dashboard is a React + TypeScript single-page application. It presents a live occupancy grid map with real-time robot pose overlay, task creation interfaces (GO\_TO, DELIVERY, PATROL), task queue monitoring, cron schedule management, and battery and connectivity indicators. Because it communicates exclusively over MQTT, it can be accessed from any network-connected device without VPN or special routing --- a mobile phone, a laptop, or a workstation at any location with internet access.

The dashboard also provides a live telepresence view via the MJPEG stream forwarded through the MQTT bridge, allowing a remote operator to see what the robot's camera sees while issuing navigation commands.

