\subsection{System Integration and Testing}
% -------------------------------------------------------

\subsubsection{Individual Unit Tests}

Each subsystem was validated independently before integration:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Navigation}: The iMRP500 was commissioned with ROS~2 and Nav2. SLAM mapping of the test environment was completed, and waypoint navigation trials confirmed the manufacturer-specified $\pm$5~cm positioning accuracy. The costmap obstacle layers (LiDAR, RGBD, inflation) were verified by placing objects at known distances and confirming avoidance behaviour.

    \item \textbf{Sensor validation}: All sensor topics were verified over the WebSocket bridge: LiDAR scans (\texttt{/scan}), RGBD point clouds (\texttt{/upcam\_data}), IMU attitude (\texttt{/imu/data}), wheel encoder odometry, battery state (\texttt{/robot\_status}), and ultrasonic proximity readings. The self-diagnosis service (\texttt{/self\_diagnosis}) was used to confirm all hardware subsystems reported healthy.

    \item \textbf{Orchestrator}: Fifteen natural-language commands of increasing complexity were submitted to the Gemini orchestrator in isolation (no robot connected), ranging from single-waypoint navigation to multi-stop conditional delivery sequences. All fifteen produced valid, executable mission plans. The streaming pipeline delivered the first step within 1.2~s of command submission on average.

    \item \textbf{Voice pipeline}: The ElevenLabs + Gemini~3.1 Live voice pipeline was tested for intelligibility, tool-call routing, and interruption handling (the user speaking while the robot is responding). All tool-calls (\texttt{robot\_control}, \texttt{plan\_and\_execute}, \texttt{cancel\_mission}) routed correctly to the client-side handlers.

    \item \textbf{MQTT telemetry}: Round-trip latency was measured by publishing 30 timestamped messages to HiveMQ Cloud and subscribing to the same topic, recording elapsed time on receipt. Results are presented in Section~\ref{sec:results}.

    \item \textbf{Body shell}: The fabricated shell was fitted to the chassis and checked against all eleven design requirements: footprint within 500~mm, total height 900~mm (within the 1,100~mm limit), mass of added structure measured and confirmed below 12~kg, display tilt verified at 40°, storage compartment accessible and functional, no sharp edges, and removable upper tray verified.
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{System Integration Tests}

With subsystems validated independently, the full system was integrated: chassis connected to tablet via Ethernet, tablet on campus WiFi, MQTT bridge active, and remote dashboard open on a separate device.

\paragraph{End-to-end delivery test.}
A delivery mission was issued by voice: the robot was instructed to navigate to a defined waypoint, announce its arrival, wait for confirmation, then return to the charging dock. The mission completed successfully across five repeated trials. The voice command was recognised, the orchestrator generated a three-step plan (navigate, speak, navigate), the mission engine executed each step, and the robot returned to dock and initiated autonomous charging.

\paragraph{Remote dashboard test.}
A navigation task was created from the remote dashboard while the robot was on the opposite side of the test space. The task appeared in the robot's queue within one MQTT cycle (approximately 1~s), and the robot began executing within one additional tick cycle (1~Hz engine). The live map and pose overlay updated continuously, and the camera stream was viewable from the remote device.

\paragraph{Voice interruption test.}
While a patrol mission was running, a voice command was issued to cancel the current mission and go to a specific waypoint. The \texttt{cancel\_mission} tool call was triggered correctly, the patrol was aborted cleanly (robot stopped, queue cleared), and the new navigation goal was dispatched within 2~s of the voice command.

\subsubsection{Acceptance Test}

The acceptance test scenario validates all six customer requirements (Chapter~3) in a single continuous sequence:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{CR1 -- Autonomous navigation}: Robot navigates from charging dock to a patient room waypoint, traversing a corridor and avoiding a dynamically placed obstacle (a trolley).
    \item \textbf{CR3 -- Patient interaction}: On arrival, the robot greets the occupant using the voice AI, provides ward information when asked, and responds to a follow-up question in English.
    \item \textbf{CR5 -- User-friendly interface}: A staff member issues a delivery task via the touch display. The robot confirms the task verbally.
    \item \textbf{CR1 -- Multi-waypoint delivery}: Robot navigates to the pharmacy waypoint, waits for a confirmation touch, then delivers to the patient room.
    \item \textbf{CR2 -- Telepresence}: A remote operator connects via the MQTT-bridged dashboard and issues a navigation command while viewing the live camera stream.
    \item \textbf{CR6 -- Autonomous charging}: Battery level threshold triggers AUTO\_CHARGE mission; robot navigates to dock and initiates charging.
\end{enumerate}

The acceptance test was completed successfully. CR4 (infection control) is addressed at the design level through material selection (acrylic and oak-veneer surfaces compatible with hospital-grade disinfectant wipes) and is not a run-time test.

% -------------------------------------------------------
\subsection{Results}
\label{sec:results}
% -------------------------------------------------------

\subsubsection{Voice-to-Action Latency}

End-to-end latency from voice command completion to first robot motion was measured across 20 trials ($N=20$). The pipeline decomposes as:

\[
\bar{t}_{\mathrm{v2a}} = t_{\mathrm{ASR}} + t_{\mathrm{LLM}} + t_{\mathrm{TTS}} + t_{\mathrm{WS}}
\]

Table~\ref{tab:latency} gives per-component statistics.

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\caption{Voice-to-action latency breakdown ($N=20$ trials).}
\label{tab:latency}
\setlength{\tabcolsep}{6pt}
\begin{tabular}{@{} l r r @{}}
\toprule
\textbf{Component} & $\bar{t}$ \textbf{(ms)} & $\sigma$ \textbf{(ms)} \\
\midrule
ElevenLabs ASR ($t_{\mathrm{ASR}}$)      & 310 & 45  \\
Gemini tool-call ($t_{\mathrm{LLM}}$)    & 790 & 180 \\
TTS streaming onset ($t_{\mathrm{TTS}}$) & 400 & 85  \\
WebSocket dispatch ($t_{\mathrm{WS}}$)   &  50 & 12  \\
\midrule
\textbf{Total} & \textbf{1550} & \textbf{310} \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

All 20 trials completed below the 3~s engineering requirement (ER3, Chapter~3), with a maximum observed latency of 2.41~s. The LLM tool-call resolution dominates at 51\% of total latency. The streaming orchestrator further reduces perceived latency by pre-firing the first navigation command before the complete plan is generated, so the robot begins moving while the voice response is still being synthesised.

\subsubsection{MQTT Telemetry Latency}

Round-trip latency between the robot bridge and HiveMQ Cloud was measured over 30 timestamped message pairs ($N=30$, measured 2026-03-25).

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\caption{MQTT round-trip latency statistics ($N=30$).}
\label{tab:mqtt}
\setlength{\tabcolsep}{6pt}
\begin{tabular}{@{} l r @{}}
\toprule
\textbf{Statistic} & \textbf{Value (ms)} \\
\midrule
Mean ($\bar{t}$)      & 159 \\
Std dev ($\sigma$)    &  30 \\
Median                & 142 \\
95th percentile       & 207 \\
Maximum               & 243 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

All messages were delivered within 243~ms. The bimodal distribution (a fast cluster at 137--157~ms and a slower cluster at 191--207~ms) reflects DPI inspection on the campus WiFi (eduroam) that introduces occasional buffering. All values are well within the limit for non-real-time telemetry; direct drive control uses the local Ethernet path and is not affected by MQTT latency.

\subsubsection{Navigation Accuracy}

Waypoint navigation accuracy was assessed over ten repeated trials to each of three defined waypoints. The iMRP500 positioning accuracy of $\pm$5~cm was confirmed in all trials. The 4-layer costmap configuration (obstacle, upward camera, downward camera, inflation) successfully avoided all statically and dynamically placed test obstacles in the acceptance test corridor without false positives causing unnecessary path deviations.

\subsubsection{Orchestrator Validation}

Fifteen natural-language commands of increasing complexity were submitted:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Single-waypoint navigation (five commands): all produced correct single-step plans.
    \item Multi-stop delivery (five commands): all produced correctly ordered multi-step sequences with confirmation steps at intermediate waypoints.
    \item Conditional return (five commands, e.g., ``if the battery is below 30\% after delivery, go to the dock; otherwise continue patrol''): all five correctly interpreted the conditional and generated branched plans.
\end{itemize}
All fifteen commands produced valid, executable mission plans. No hallucinated waypoints or malformed step types were observed.

% -------------------------------------------------------
\subsection{Standards Compliance}
% -------------------------------------------------------

The following standards were applied during design and integration:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{ISO~13482:2014} (Safety requirements for personal care robots): The 0.8~m/s maximum navigation speed and 0.8~m inflation radius in the costmap satisfy the velocity and proximity limits specified for robots operating in human-shared environments.
    \item \textbf{ISO~13850} (Emergency stop): The hardware emergency stop relay was tested to confirm that the robot halts within one control cycle ($<$100~ms) on E-stop activation. The soft-stop service (\texttt{/soft\_stop}) provides a software-level equivalent.
    \item \textbf{ITU-T H.264} (Video compression): The MJPEG camera stream and the MQTT-forwarded video feed use standard compressed formats compatible with web browsers.
    \item \textbf{IEEE~802.11} (Wireless LAN): The MQTT bridge and cloud AI APIs operate over the standard campus WiFi infrastructure with no modifications to network equipment.
    \item \textbf{Hospital materials}: Body shell surfaces (acrylic, oak veneer) were selected to be compatible with isopropyl-alcohol-based disinfectant wipes used in clinical environments.
\end{itemize}

