At USD~3,240, TAMRA delivers the same functional envelope as commercial hospital AMRs priced between USD~12,000 and USD~47,500 --- a 73\% cost reduction compared to the nearest commercially available platform with equivalent capability. The open-source software stack (ROS~2, Nav2, standard web technologies) carries no licensing cost.

% -------------------------------------------------------
\subsection{Conclusion}
% -------------------------------------------------------

Chapter~5 has documented the full implementation of TAMRA, from the platform transition decision through hardware commissioning, body shell fabrication, software development, and system integration. The iMRP500 was selected after a rigorous eight-platform comparison and reverse-engineered to expose its full sensor suite over a documented WebSocket API. The body shell was designed through a three-stage workflow combining generative concept synthesis, AI-assisted 3D mesh generation, and parametric engineering refinement in Fusion~360, and fabricated locally in Oman within budget and mass constraints. The software stack --- a semantic task orchestrator, voice pipeline, mission engine, MQTT bridge, and remote dashboard --- was developed in parallel with the hardware procurement and completed before integration began.

Measured results confirm voice-to-action latency of $1.55 \pm 0.31$~s (all 20~trials below the 3~s requirement), MQTT round-trip of $159 \pm 30$~ms (all 30~trials below 250~ms), navigation accuracy of $\pm$5~cm, and 100\% plan generation success across 15~orchestrator test commands. The acceptance test scenario, validating all six customer requirements in a single continuous sequence, was completed successfully. The system is realised at USD~3,240 on an open, extensible architecture.
